    "narrative": "For Ghost Ride the WHIP on this May 2nd slate, **Tyler Soderstrom** leads the charge with a 76.84 efficiency score, buoyed by a favorable matchup against Cecconi and an optimal batting order slot. **Trevor Story** remains a high-upside play at 73.82; while his base projection is moderate, the combination of a slow opposing delivery\u2014signaling a high probability for stolen bases\u2014and a park factor favoring power hitters makes him a must-start despite the aggressive internal rating. Similarly, **Vinnie Pasquantino** secures a 70.89 score by leveraging a significant platoon advantage against Hancock, providing reliable run production in a high-leverage utility spot.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Travis Bazzana** on the bench despite his elite 0.408 xwOBA. While his underlying metrics are top-tier, the L/L platoon disadvantage against Lopez, J coupled with a lower lineup position pushed his efficiency score to 46.50, keeping him just behind **Brice Turang** and **Luis Campusano** for active status. Meanwhile, **Jose Caballero** sits on the outside looking in with a 39.32 score; despite his elite stolen base potential, the sharp decline in effectiveness against Bradish and the restrictive \"Below Floor\" threshold made his benching mandatory to preserve our limited game caps. \n\nManagers should monitor **Corbin Carroll** closely; despite his strong 64.74 score, he faces a stern test against the pitching profile of Imanaga. While his elite sprint speed and favorable order placement mitigate risk, the defensive skill of the opposition acts as a ceiling on his expected output. We are effectively betting on the speed/OBP combination of **James Wood** at the top of the order and the platoon-adjusted power of **Josh Naylor** to carry our offensive categories tonight, while remaining wary of the bench depth held by **Kyle Karros** and **Cole Young** should any late-inning defensive substitutions shift our configuration.",
